author: Gregor Stuart Hunter
title: Markets in Asia Start Higher After U.S. Jobs Data
text:
HONG KONG—Asian markets started the week higher after weaker-than-expected U.S. jobs data released Friday reduced expectations of a rate increase from the Federal Reserve, though with several markets closed volumes are expected to remain thin.
Data released Friday showed nonfarm payrolls rose by 142,000 in September, sharply below economists’ estimates, leaving the unemployment rate unchanged at 5.1%.
